{{Refimprove|date=April 2009}}
The '''Neutrino Array Radio Calibration (NARC)''' experiment is the successor to the [[Radio Ice Cerenkov Experiment|Radio Ice Cherenkov Experiment (RICE)]] which will serve as a testbed for future development of an eventual large-scale neutrino radio-detection array. NARC involves detecting ultra high energy electron [[neutrino]]s through their interactions with ice molecules in the Antarctic icecap, based on the principle of [[Coherence (physics)|radio coherence]]. Experimentally, the goal is to detect and measure long-wavelength (radiofrequency) pulses resulting from this interaction.

