'''Pseudoenzymes''' are variants of [[enzyme]]s (usually [[protein]]s) that are catalytically deficient (usually inactive), meaning that they perform little or no [[enzyme catalysis]]. They are believed to be represented in all major [[Protein family|enzyme families]] in the [[kingdoms of life]]. Pseudoenzymes are becoming increasingly important to analyse, especially as the [[bioinformatic]] analysis of [[genome]]s reveals their ubiquity. Their important regulatory and sometimes disease-associated functions in metabolic and [[signalling pathway]]s are also shedding new light on the non-catalytic functions of active enzymes ([[Protein moonlighting]]), and are suggesting new ways to target and interpret cellular signalling mechanisms using [[small molecule]]s and drugs.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Eyers PA, Murphy JM | title = The evolving world of pseudoenzymes: proteins, prejudice and zombies | journal = BMC Biology | volume = 14 | issue = 1 | pages = 98 | date = November 2016 | pmid = 27835992 | pmc = 5106787 | doi = 10.1186/s12915-016-0322-x }}</ref> The most intensively analyzed, and certainly the best understood pseudoenzymes in terms of cellular signalling functions are probably the [[pseudokinase]]s, the pseudoproteases and the pseudophosphatases.
==Structures and roles== The difference between enzymatically active and inactive [[Sequence homology|homologues]] has been noted (and in some cases, understood when comparing catalytically active and inactive proteins residing in recognisable families) for some time at the sequence level,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Todd AE, Orengo CA, Thornton JM | title = Sequence and structural differences between enzyme and nonenzyme homologs | journal = Structure | volume = 10 | issue = 10 | pages = 1435–51 | date = October 2002 | pmid = 12377129 | doi = 10.1016/s0969-2126(02)00861-4 }}</ref> and some pseudoenzymes have also been referred to as 'prozymes' when they were analysed in [[protozoan parasite]]s.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Willert EK, Fitzpatrick R, Phillips MA | title = Allosteric regulation of an essential trypanosome polyamine biosynthetic enzyme by a catalytically dead homolog | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 104 | issue = 20 | pages = 8275–80 | date = May 2007 | pmid = 17485680 | pmc = 1895940 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0701111104 }}</ref> The best studied pseudoenzymes reside amongst various key signalling superfamilies of enzymes, such as the [[protease]]s,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Adrain C, Freeman M | title = New lives for old: evolution of pseudoenzyme function illustrated by iRhoms | journal = Nature Reviews. Molecular Cell Biology | volume = 13 | issue = 8 | pages = 489–98 | date = July 2012 | pmid = 22781900 | doi = 10.1038/nrm3392 }}</ref> the [[protein kinase]]s,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Manning G, Whyte DB, Martinez R, Hunter T, Sudarsanam S | title = The protein kinase complement of the human genome | journal = Science | volume = 298 | issue = 5600 | pages = 1912–34 | date = December 2002 | pmid = 12471243 | doi = 10.1126/science.1075762 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Boudeau J, Miranda-Saavedra D, Barton GJ, Alessi DR | title = Emerging roles of pseudokinases | journal = Trends in Cell Biology | volume = 16 | issue = 9 | pages = 443–52 | date = September 2006 | pmid = 16879967 | doi = 10.1016/j.tcb.2006.07.003 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Eyers PA, Keeshan K, Kannan N | title = Tribbles in the 21st Century: The Evolving Roles of Tribbles Pseudokinases in Biology and Disease | journal = Trends in Cell Biology | volume = 27 | issue = 4 | pages = 284–298 | date = April 2017 | pmid = 27908682 | pmc = 5382568 | doi = 10.1016/j.tcb.2016.11.002 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Reiterer V, Eyers PA, Farhan H | title = Day of the dead: pseudokinases and pseudophosphatases in physiology and disease | journal = Trends in Cell Biology | volume = 24 | issue = 9 | pages = 489–505 | date = September 2014 | pmid = 24818526 | doi = 10.1016/j.tcb.2014.03.008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Murphy JM, Czabotar PE, Hildebrand JM, Lucet IS, Zhang JG, Alvarez-Diaz S, Lewis R, Lalaoui N, Metcalf D, Webb AI, Young SN, Varghese LN, Tannahill GM, Hatchell EC, Majewski IJ, Okamoto T, Dobson RC, Hilton DJ, Babon JJ, Nicola NA, Strasser A, Silke J, Alexander WS | title = The pseudokinase MLKL mediates necroptosis via a molecular switch mechanism | journal = Immunity | volume = 39 | issue = 3 | pages = 443–53 | date = September 2013 | pmid = 24012422 | doi = 10.1016/j.immuni.2013.06.018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wishart MJ, Dixon JE | title = Gathering STYX: phosphatase-like form predicts functions for unique protein-interaction domains | journal = Trends in Biochemical Sciences | volume = 23 | issue = 8 | pages = 301–6 | date = August 1998 | pmid = 9757831 | doi = 10.1016/s0968-0004(98)01241-9 }}</ref> protein phosphatases <ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Reiterer V, Eyers PA, Farhan H | title = Day of the dead: pseudokinases and pseudophosphatases in physiology and disease | journal = Trends in Cell Biology | volume = 24 | issue = 9 | pages = 489–505 | date = September 2014 | pmid = 24818526 | doi = 10.1016/j.tcb.2014.03.008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Chen MJ, Dixon JE, Manning G | title = Genomics and evolution of protein phosphatases | journal = Science Signaling | volume = 10 | issue = 474 | pages = eaag1796 | date = April 2017 | pmid = 28400531 | doi = 10.1126/scisignal.aag1796 }}</ref> and [[ubiquitin]] modifying enzymes.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Zeqiraj E, Tian L, Piggott CA, Pillon MC, Duffy NM, Ceccarelli DF, Keszei AF, Lorenzen K, Kurinov I, Orlicky S, Gish GD, Heck AJ, Guarné A, Greenberg RA, Sicheri F | title = Higher-Order Assembly of BRCC36-KIAA0157 Is Required for DUB Activity and Biological Function | journal = Molecular Cell | volume = 59 | issue = 6 | pages = 970–83 | date = September 2015 | pmid = 26344097 | pmc = 4579573 | doi = 10.1016/j.molcel.2015.07.028 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Strickson S, Emmerich CH, Goh ET, Zhang J, Kelsall IR, Macartney T, Hastie CJ, Knebel A, Peggie M, Marchesi F, Arthur JS, Cohen P | title = Roles of the TRAF6 and Pellino E3 ligases in MyD88 and RANKL signaling | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 114 | issue = 17 | pages = E3481-E3489 | date = April 2017 | pmid = 28404732 | pmc = 5410814 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1702367114 }}</ref> The role of pseudoenzymes as "pseudo scaffolds" has also been recognised <ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Aggarwal-Howarth S, Scott JD | title = Pseudoscaffolds and anchoring proteins: the difference is in the details | journal = Biochemical Society Transactions | volume = 45 | issue = 2 | pages = 371–379 | date = April 2017 | pmid = 28408477 | pmc = 5497583 | doi = 10.1042/bst20160329 }}</ref> and pseudoenzymes are now beginning to be more thoroughly studied in terms of their biology and function, in large part because they are also interesting potential targets (or anti-targets) for drug design in the context of intracellular cellular signalling complexes.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Foulkes DM, Byrne DP, Bailey FP, Eyers PA | title = Tribbles pseudokinases: novel targets for chemical biology and drug discovery? | journal = Biochemical Society Transactions | volume = 43 | issue = 5 | pages = 1095–103 | date = October 2015 | pmid = 26517930 | doi = 10.1042/bst20150109 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Byrne DP, Foulkes DM, Eyers PA | title = Pseudokinases: update on their functions and evaluation as new drug targets | journal = Future Medicinal Chemistry | volume = 9 | issue = 2 | pages = 245–265 | date = January 2017 | pmid = 28097887 | doi = 10.4155/fmc-2016-0207 }}</ref>
